# Lesson 3.1: Stakeholder Interviews & Functional Requirements

**Unit:** 3 — Open-Ended Projects  
**Duration:** 1–2 class periods  
**Prerequisite:** All of Unit 0 and Unit 1; taught immediately before Project 2

---

## Learning Objectives

By the end of this lesson, students will be able to:
- Define what a stakeholder is in the context of design
- Explain the difference between wants, needs, and constraints
- Convert stakeholder feedback into written functional requirements
- Conduct a basic stakeholder interview using open-ended questions
- Document interview results in a structured format

---

## What Is a Stakeholder?

A **stakeholder** is anyone who has a meaningful interest in the outcome of a design — anyone who will be affected by whether it works well or poorly.

In Project 2, your stakeholders will be real people with real problems:
- A student who needs a sock holder
- A model rocketry enthusiast who needs a component
- Someone in your school community who has a physical need you can address

Your job as the designer is not to guess what they need — it's to **ask** and **listen**.

---

## Why Interviewing Matters

The most common design failure is solving the wrong problem. A designer who jumps straight to building often creates something technically impressive that doesn't actually meet the user's real need.

Consider this scenario: A person says they need a "better way to organize their desk." An impulsive designer immediately starts designing a fancy pencil holder. But through an interview, you discover they spend 10 minutes every morning looking for their phone charger — the real problem is cable management, not pencils.

**The interview is how you find out what problem you're actually solving.**

---

## Wants, Needs, and Constraints

Before you design anything, you need to sort stakeholder input into three categories:

| Category | Definition | Example |
|----------|-----------|---------|
| **Need** | Must-have; the design fails without it | "It has to hold the socks flat so they don't bunch" |
| **Want** | Nice-to-have; improves the design but not essential | "I'd love it if it came in blue" |
| **Constraint** | A limitation you must work within | "It has to fit on a shelf that's 15 cm deep" |

When you write **functional requirements**, you are turning needs into testable statements. A well-written functional requirement:
- Describes **what** the design must do (not **how** it does it)
- Is specific enough that you can test pass/fail
- Does not assume a particular solution

**Examples:**

| Bad (assumes solution) | Good (testable behavior) |
|----------------------|------------------------|
| "Must have velcro" | "Must be removable and re-attachable without tools" |
| "Should be made of PLA" | "Must withstand foot traffic from furniture" |
| "Needs to look nice" | "Must be unobtrusive enough that visitors don't notice it" |

